				h1.articleheading FIVE DEADEYE CARDS TO WATCH OUT FOR

				img(src='../../images/de/explosiverounds.png').articlefivevertimg
				h2.articlefiveheading Explosive Rounds
				h3.articlefivetext Two points of Aim alongside 3 damage to any target is a great deal. This card is a signpost for what Deadeye does best - big damage out of nowhere.

				img(src='../../images/de/newclip.png').articlefivehorzimg
				h2.articlefiveheading New Clip
				h3.articlefivetext Deadeye really struggles with finding extra cards to keep her hand full, so New Clip is great to have on-demand whenever you might need it. This may come at a risk if your opponent is too aggressive! 

				img(src='../../images/cross/thwip.png').articlefivehorzimg
				h2.articlefiveheading Thwip!
				h3.articlefivetext Deadeye's sister Thwip! deals with any problem for one turn and sticks around to brawl afterwards. With her decent armor and ability to protect your Aim combo pieces, this card will help you win games.

				img(src='../../images/de/spoilsofwar.png').articlefivehorzimg
				h2.articlefiveheading Spoils Of War
				h3.articlefivetext You might need a bit of incentive to include this in your deck, but in Deadeye's discard strategy this is a powerful engine for keeping your opponents hand size down. It's also great insurance against another discard player.	

				img(src='../../images/de/duckdown.png').articlefivevertimg
				h2.articlefiveheading Duck Down
				h3.articlefivetext You can use Duck Down to grab crossovers, powerful defensive options like Decent Cover or a scope to improve your Aim. Don't count this one out.

